Step 1: Problem Understanding

After receiving the question, first explain the problem statement to the interviewer in simple and clear English.

Describe what the problem is asking.

Explain the goal of the problem.

Use one sample input/output example given in the question itself to explain how the solution should work.

The goal of this step is to ensure the interviewer clearly understands that you fully grasp the problem.‚Ä®‚Ä®Mention edge case (if any present) or write any questions that can asked to interviewer to make discussion interactive. 

Step 2: Discuss Different Approaches

Explain all possible approaches to solve the problem:

Start with the brute-force approach.

Explain what you would do step-by-step in this approach.

Discuss its time and space complexity.

Clearly explain why this approach is not optimal (for example, high time or space complexity).

If multiple alternative approaches exist, briefly mention them.

Finally, transition toward the optimal solution.

Step 3: Explain the Optimal Approach in Detail

Explain the most optimal solution in depth:

Explain why this approach is optimal.

Clearly mention which data structures you are using and why.

Explain how this approach improves time complexity and space complexity compared to the brute-force solution.

Justify your design decisions logically, as if you are convincing the interviewer.

Step 4: Step-by-Step Algorithm

Provide a clear, step-by-step algorithm in plain English describing how you will solve the problem.

Each step should be easy to follow.

Avoid code here‚Äîfocus only on logic and flow.

Step 5: Java Code Implementation

Write the Java function code only.

Code requirements:

Each line must contain two comments:

One comment explaining what the line does.

One comment showing a dry-run explanation (how data flows through that line using an example).

The code should strictly follow the algorithm explained above.

Do not include the full class, main method, or unnecessary boilerplate.

